<Base
  title="CAST · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="Given a modal state — a set of possible worlds and a modal constraint — CAST projects it to controlled text in English, German, and Chinese, and grades whether a model tracks the world-set or the words."
  toc={true}
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Supporting workbench · modal compiler (formerly MiniCausalLang)
    </div>
    <h1>CAST — one modal state, many languages</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      Given a modal state, generate controlled language — then check the model tracks the surviving world-set, not the words.
    </p>

    <p>
      CAST starts from a <em>known modal state</em> — a candidate set of possible worlds
      <code>W = {"{w₁…w₄}"}</code> plus a ◇/□ constraint — runs the elimination, and
      <strong>projects the surviving world-set to controlled text</strong> in English, German, and
      Chinese ("cannot possibly be" / "kann unmöglich … sein" / "不可能是"). Correct behaviour is not
      picking one world but <em>indifference over exactly the survivors</em>. Because the logical
      content is fixed by construction, any difference across the three languages can only come from
      linguistic form — and structure recovery can be scored against a known target rather than
      guessed. This is the workbench the modal-concepts thesis runs on.
    </p>

    <p>
      The general machine is a <strong>compiler from a formal-semantic object to multilingual text</strong>,
      where "evaluation" means checking the model's behaviour is isomorphic to the pre-compilation
      object. Its <strong>first domain is the causal graph</strong> (below) — the sandbox that made
      the certification cut decidable — and the modal-state compiler above is the general form.
      Minimal pairs are single-variable operations at the formal layer (swap a predicate for an
      extensionally identical fictional twin; add a retraction), and the surface is always
      regenerated, never hand-edited.
    </p>

    <MiniCausalFigure />

    <p>
      The hard direction in my <a href="/writing/inferential-productivity">note on inferential
      productivity</a> is reverse: given a behavior, what is the <em>smallest</em> causal structure
      that has to be there? On a real model, there is usually no ground truth against which to score
      a recovered structure. CAST keeps the bridge explicit before trusting the method
      elsewhere: specify the grammar, compile it into a causal graph, enumerate the inferences that
      graph licenses, train or evaluate a model on that data, and test whether behavioral recovery
      returns the structure that was actually planted.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is supporting infrastructure, not a paper in its own right. It exists to make the link
      between linguistic form and the formal-semantic structure it encodes — causal structure in the
      first domain, modal structure in the next — explicit enough to be falsifiable against a known
      answer.
    </p>

    <hr/>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">An interactive workbench — specify a grammar, compile the graph, see what recovery returns — will live here.</p>
  </article>
</Base>
